Gascoigne tells us (p. 190) that while the Commons were wrangling with the King’s young counsellors at Leicester, and the young counsellors were trying to browbeat the Gemmeus, and ⁸ before the settlement of many articles in that Parliament³ the commons os Kent rose under their Captain John Cade, who was descended from a base-born Roger Mortimer, and that this captain, after pardon granted to him and his by the King‚ was mortally wounded by the troeson os his servant, and brought dead to London in July, 145o.’

The fifteen articles contained in the complaint of the commons of Kent are well known. They do not, however, occur in the Rolls of Par- liament. They are, speaking generally, identical with those grievances of which the Commons complained, which they had been striving, both in London and Leicester‚ to redress. The battle of Sevenoaks was followed by the occupation of Southwark, the entry into London, the behoeding os Lord Fiennes and his son-in-law, Cromer, the sheriff of Kent‚ and the battle os London Bridge. This fight was indecisive, and the King‚ taking advantage of the opportunity, issued a pardon. The expedient had the usual effect, and the insurgents dispersed. Cade, after · taking his goods to Rochester‚ and having attempted unsuccessfully to seize Queenborough Castle, fled to Lewes, where he was slain‚ and the in- surrection was at an end. How grave it was is to be seen in the attainder of Cade, and in the number of persons who sor some years afterwards were charged with complicity in the outbreak. Among these was Sir W’m. Oldhall‚ Speaker of the Commons in the Parliament os Nov. 1450, who was outlawed in 1453, sor having been a favourer os Cade. Cade himself prosessed to believe that the King’s pardon was invalid unless it were affirmed by Parliament.
